 Off-farm work decisions on Dutch cash crop farms 
 and the 1992 and (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP changes 
 Tassew Woldehanna, Alfons Oude Lansink, Jack Peerlings * 
 Department of Money flow and Management, Wageningen University, Hollandseweg 1, 6706 KN Wageningen, The Netherlands 
 
 Received 19 June 1997; received in changed form 18 August 1999; accepted 20 September 1999 
 
 Abstract 
 A double hurdle model of off-farm work participation and off-farm labour income was received/made from and guessed consistent 
 with a farm household model. It was found that restricting and unexpected transaction costs stop farm families from 
 participating in off-farm work. The 1992 and the (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP changes are most likely to increase the off-farm 
 employment of plantable farm families, but its full effect cannot happen/be made real because of fears to enter off-farm activities. 
 Household and farm (features/ qualities/ traits) have different hits/effects on off-farm work participation and on the level of off-farm labour 
 income. Â© 2000 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: Off-farm work participation; Off-farm labour income; Double hurdle model; Dutch plantable farms; CAP reform 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 The 1992 (related to Europe) Union (EU) common farming-based policy (CAP) reform has changed the relative 
 role of price support and direct income support in 
 plantable farming (Oude Lansink and Peerlings, 1996). It 
 reduced the price support for cereals and stopped the 
 shortage payments for oilseeds. Instead (making up for something/paying for something) land payments which act as direct income 
 support were introduced. A further reduction in price 
 support in combination with increased (making up for something/paying for something) 
 land payments will happen in 2000 and 2001 as 
 a result of the decisions taken on (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 
 ((related to Europe) Union, 1999). 
 
 *corresponding author. Tel.: +317-483812; fax: +317-484736. 
 E-mail address: jack.peerlings@alg.aae.wag-ur.nl (J. Peerlings). 
 
 These policy changes may affect the labour portion offarmers between farm and off-farm activities. It 
 may also encourage farmers to (branch out into different things) their income 
 sources (Hill, 1996). In a farm household, labour is 
 gave out between farm and off-farm work such that 
 the not important value of farm labour equals the wage rate 
 of off-farm work (Becker, 1965; Gronau, 1973). Books in off-farm work also points to/shows (see Hallberg et 
 al., 1991) that farm families' off-farm work decision is dependent on location, farm and non-farm 
 income, and family and (money-related) (features/ qualities/ traits) (Woman 
 et al., 1991). It is inversely related to farm income 
 because of a substitution and income effect. Nonlabour incomes such as income from valuable things, social 
 security benefits, and direct income support reduce 
 off-farm employment due to an income effect only. 
 As a result, a change in government policy due to 
 either a price policy or direct income support (e.g. 
 
