 coming from the 1992 and (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP 
 changes) may affect the desire of farm families 
 to participate in off-farm work. 
 However, in the presence of restricting and transaction costs in the labour market, the not important value of 
 farm labour and the wage rate of off-farm work may 
 not be equal. In such cases, families cannot execute 
 their desired plan to work off their farm (Deaton and 
 Irish, 1984; Blundell and Meghir, 1987). So the 
 possible effect of the CAP changes on off-farm work 
 may not be fully (understood/made real/achieved). 
 Capital and technology employed by a farm household, person's age and education can have either a 
 negative or positive effect on the desire of farm families to parncipate in off-farm work as they affect 
 both farm and off-farm employment (Woman  et al., 1991). 
 More than that, the relative importance of these factors may 
 differ across families (Woman  et al., 1991). Although 
 well recorded/supported for North America (see, for example, Hallberg et al., 1991), books on off-farm work 
 is rare/not enough  for the Netherlands and Europe as a whole. 
 What's more, previous studies made on off-farm work 
 (Olfert, 1993; Kimhi, 1994, 1996; Hearn et al., 1996; 
 Kimhi and Lee, 1996; Mishra and Goodwin, 1997; 
 Tavernier et al., 1997; Weersink et al., 1998) do not 
 think about/believe restricting in the off-farm labour market. 
 The goals of this study are therefore (1) to 
 (ask lots of questions about/try to find the truth about) the effect of farm and non-labour income 
 on the off-farm work decision and decide/figure out the effects/results/suggestions of the 1992 and (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP changes; (2) 
 to (ask lots of questions about/try to find the truth about) the role of other (things that decide other things) of offfarm work; and (3) to test if Dutch plantable farm families are actually stopped by restricting and unexpected 
 transaction costs to enter off-farm activities. 
 Off-farm work participation and off-farm labour 
 income are modelled agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with a farm household 
 model (Singh et al., 1986; Huffman, 1991). More than that, 
 this paper uses a double hurdle model (Deaton and 
 Irish, 1984; Blundell and Meghir, 1987) and generalised Tobit model (Amemiya, 1984) in which the 
 participation decision and off-farm labour income 
 are both/together guessed using a maximum chance 
 estimator (MLE). 
 The rest of the paper is organised as follows. In the 
 next section, explanation and model (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) are 
 discussed. In Section 3, the data and guess methods are described. Section 4 discusses the results. 
 Section 5 presents the ends/end results. 
 
