 2.1. Independent models 
 The ordinary Tobit model assumes that the same 
 (random/including random data points) process affects both the participation decision and off-farm labour income. A zero (understanding/achieving a goal) for 
 a (thing that changes (like a test score) because of something else that you control (like study time)) represents a corner solution or a 
 negative value for the hidden (under) hidden/covered up dependent 
 (number or thing that changes) (Cragg, 1971; Lin and Schmidt, 1984 ). When 
 a Tobit model is taken from the idea (you think is true) that the 
 error term of the participation equation and the hidden/covered up 
 (number or thing that changes) are related, it is called generalised Tobit 
 model (Amemiya, 1984, pp. 29-33). 
 Even if farm families are willing to participate in 
 off-farm work, however, restricting in the labour market (Deaton and Irish, 1984; Blundell and Meghir, 
 1987) and unexpected transaction costs such as search 
 costs, information and other costs may stop them to 
 participate in off-farm work. In the presence of (fear/stopping of behavior) to join the off-farm activities, therefore, a doublehurdle model would be more appropriate than an 
 ordinary Tobit model (Cragg, 1971; Blundell and 
 Meghir, 1987, p. 197). The double hurdle model takes 
 into account that people have to pass two hurdles 
 to participate in off-farm work: they have to develop 
 the want to participate in off-farm work and pass the 
 (fear/stopping of behavior) to join the labour market. If the relationship 
 between the error terms in the participation decision 
 and off-farm labour income is assumed to be zero, 
 then the model is called independent double hurdle 
 model or in short the model of Cragg (1971). In 
 contrast, if the independence idea (you think is true) for the 
 error terms of the participation decision and off-farm 
 labour income is relaxed, it is called dependent double 
 hurdle model (Deaton and Irish, 1984; Blundell and 
 Meghir, 1987). 
 Following the lines of Maddala (1983), Amemiya 
 (Amemiya, 1984, p. 9) and Blundell and Meghir 
 (Blundell and Meghir, 1987, p. 181 ), the log chance 
 function of the Tobit model can be written as: 
 
 logL= 
 
