 3. Data and guess 
 
 y 1 - p- 
 
 When p is zero, it reduces to the model of Cragg 
 (1971), if &amp;lt;1&amp;gt;(1X1X) is one it reduces to a generalised 
 Tobit model (Amemiya, 1984), whereas, if p is zero 
 and &amp;lt;1&amp;gt;(1X1X) equals one, it reduces to a standard Tobit 
 model. 
 Explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) (X's) were chosen to be 
 expected short-run farm (money made/good thing received), on-farm labour supplied by the head of the household and other family 
 members, land, capital, time, non-labour income such 
 as such as income from valuable things, social security benefits; 
 household (features/ qualities/ traits) such as age, education dummies, and family size, macroeconomics conditions 
 such as the personal price index and average market 
 wage rates. All (numbers that change/things that change) except expected short-run 
 farm (money made/good thing received) are assumed to be (coming from the outside of something). These (numbers that change/things that change) affect both the reservation wage rate and the 
 market wage rate, and can be came/coming from an farming-based household model (Huffman, 1991). 
 Expected short-run farm (money made/good thing received) has been received/made from 
 from a (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ised quadratic profit function (may or may not happen, depending on something) on fixed inputs. It was assumed that output 
 prices were not known at the time decisions were 
 made on planting. Because of this, expected rather than (understood/made real/achieved) prices were used. Expected output prices were 
 built by applying an AR(l) filter to the price of 
 output. To (force (on people)/cause an inconvenient situation) linear evenness the profit function is (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ised by the price of output (Thijssen, 
 1992, p. 31). The (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ised quadratic short-run (money made/good thing received) 
 
 Data on (focused on doing one thing very well) plantable farms, covering the 
 period 1971/72-1992/93, come from a layered sample of farms keeping accounts for the LEIDLO farm accounting system2 . In total 912 individual 
 farms forming an unbalanced panel of 4110 (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) were used for the analysis. Summary statistics of 
 the data used are given in Table 1. A more described/explained 
 description of the sample used in this study can be 
 found in LEI-DLO (1992). 
 Family labour makes up/is equal to 88% of total labour used 
 on the farm, whereas hired labour makes up for the 
 remaining 12%. 37% of the (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) reported no 
 use of hired labour at all. Out of the sample, 47% of the 
 farms have positive off-farm labour income. What's more, out of the 4110 (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements), 65% ofthem have 
 medium and higher level farming-based education, 22% 
 of them have lower level farming-based education and 
 2.7% of them have general education. 
 Expected short-run farm (money made/good thing received) was serious and stubborn as 
 the expected price of output times output amount 
 minus the value of changeable inputs. There is one output 
 (composed of cereals, sugar red vegetable, potatoes and other 
 outputs) and one changeable input (fertiliser, seeds, bug-killers, hired labour and other (number or thing that changes) inputs). Tornqvist price indices (at 1980/81 prices) were calculated 
