 estimator was rejected (see also Greene, 1993, pp. 
 479-480). A random effect estimator was also used for 
 the Tobit model of the off-farm labour income. The 
 panel data nature of the data used was not accounted 
 
 for in the guess of the double hurdle model and 
 the generalised Tobit model of off-farm work participation and off-farm labour income; these were guessed using MLE. 
 
 4. Results 
 Limit/guideline guesses of the profit function can be 
 found in Table 2. The guessed profit function (9) fits 
 the data well with an (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) R 2 of 0. 70. What's more, 
 the profit function is monotonically increasing with 
 respect to the fixed inputs (labour, capital, land and 
 technology), decreasing and curving out in the (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ised 
 price of changeable inputs. 
 First, a Tobit model (3) and Cragg model (4) were 
 guessed in order to test for fears to participate 
 in off-farm activities (Table 3). The Tobit model is 
 rejected significantll suggesting that farm families 
 are shy to do/complete their desired plan to participate in off-farm activities. The computation of the 
 dependent double hurdle model (8) was, however, 
 found to be heavy and difficult and full coming together was not 
 
