 NS points to/shows unimportantly different from zero at 5% level for the guessed coefficients. 
 b The indirect effect comes through the effect on the expected short-run fann (money made/good thing received). 
 c When the output price increases by 1%, short-run expected farm (makes money/gets something good) increase by 1.02%. 
 a 
 
 possible to (accomplish or gain with effort) (Results of the dependent double 
 hurdle model are not given in this paper). Next, the 
 generalised Tobit model (7) was guessed. The relationship-related coefficient (p) is not very different 
 from zero pointing to/showing that it is not worthwhile to use the 
 limit/guideline guesses of the generalised Tobit model for 
 further analysis. Because of this, the results of the independent 
 double hurdle model have been used for further analysis and (understandings/ explanations). The results are summarised 
 in terms of almost-elasticities4 (Cramer, 1991, p. 8) for 
 the chance of participating in off-farm work and 
 elasticities for the off-farm labour income (Table 4). 
 Expected short-run farm (money made/good thing received) has a significant 
 bad effect on both the participation decision 
 and the level of off-farm labour income, but with 
 stronger hit/effect on the level of off-farm labour income 
 than on the want to participate. Non-labour income 
 did not show any significant effect on both the participation decision and off-farm labour income. An 
 increase in the output price by 1% increases expected 
 
 4 We use almost-ability to stretch for the participation decision since for a 
 chance response almost-ability to stretch is unit free. 
 
 short-run farm make money by 1.02% and the want to 
 participate in off-farm work decreases by 0.06%, 
 and decreases the off-farm labour income by 0.99% 
 on the average. So the 1992 and (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP 
 changes which decrease price support are most likely 
 to increase off-farm employment of farm families. 
 Family size, general education and age of the household head have a significant effect on the participation 
 decision, but an unimportant effect on the level of offfarm labour income. Family size increases the families' want to participate in off-farm work, which is 
 agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the explanation. Families with a larger 
 family size have (compared to other things) higher not important utility of 
 income and a stronger want to participate in off-farm 
 work. General education of the household head has a 
 little but positive significant effect on the participation 
 decision (Huffman, 1980). Farming-based education 
 does not show any significant effect on the off-farm 
 work decision at all. Age and age squared of the 
 household head show a significant quadratic age pattern on the participation decision which is consistent 
 with the life-cycle guess (Sumner, 1982). On the 
 average, the desire of families to participate in offfarm work reaches its peak at the household head's age 
 
 170 
 
 T. Woldehanna et al./Agricultural Money flow 22 (2000) 163-171 
 
 of 41 years. This hints the number of dual 
 employment among young farmers and full time farming among older farmers (Benjamin and Guyomard, 
 1994). However, neither age nor age squared showed 
 any significant effect on the level of off-farm labour 
 income. 
 When the on-farm labour supply of the household 
 head increases, both the want to participate in offfarm work and the off-farm labour income decrease. 
 The direct effect of other family members' on-farm 
 labour supply is not very different from zero 
 in both the participation decision and the level of 
 off-farm labour income, but it has a little effect 
 indirectly through its effect on expected short-run 
 farm (money made/good thing received). 
 Farm (features/ qualities/ traits) such as land, capital and technology have a negative indirect hit/effect on both the offfarm work participation decision and the level of offfarm labour income. Whereas the direct effects of 
 capital and technology are positive for off-farm labour 
 income, they are not very different from zero 
 for the participation decision. As a result capital 
 and technology have a net negative effect on the 
 participation decision and a net positive effect on 
 the level of off-farm labour income. Land has a 
 significant positive direct effect and negative indirect 
 effect on the want to participate in off-farm work. 
 The direct effect rules the indirect effect and the 
 net effect turns out to be positive. But its direct effect 
 on the level of off-farm labour income is not significant and the net effect turns out to be negative. The 
 positive net effect of capital and technology on the 
 level of off-farm labour income may be due to the fact 
 that capital and technology employed by families 
 have a labour saving character. The net positive effect 
 of land on the off-farm work participation decision is a 
 strange result, which cannot be explained within the 
 (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) of a new-classical money-based explanation. 
 The personal price index (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ised by the price 
 of output shows a large and significant positive effect 
 on the level of off-farm labour income and a negative 
 but unimportant effect on the off-farm work participation decision. This illustrates that as the consumption 
 price increases the not important utility of fun decreases 
 and the strength of off-farm work increases. The 
 average market wage rate, which is invariant across 
 families, does not show any significant effect on the 
 off-farm work decision. 
 
 5. Ends/end results 
 The results confirm that farm families are shy by restricting and unexpected transaction costs 
 to participate in off-farm activities. Expected shortrun farm (money made/good thing received) and on-farm labour supplied by a 
 household head have a strong bad effect on 
 the off-farm work decision of a household. Whereas, 
 non-labour income, on-farm labour supplied by other 
 family members and farming-based education do not 
 show any significant hit/effect on the off-farm work 
 decision. Family size and general education show a 
 positive effect on the desire of families to participate in off-farm work, but not on the level of off-farm 
 labour income. Age of the household head shows 
 a significant quadratic pattern in the participation 
 decision only. 
 The policy hint/result/effect is that government payments 
 aimed at increasing household's income through price 
 policies may worsens/decreases the off-farm 
 employment of farm families. Whereas, direct 
 income support does not create a bad thing for 
 families to participate in off-farm work. Because of this, 
 the 1992 and (list of things to deal with/desire to reach a goal) 2000 CAP changes, decreased 
 price support in combination with direct income support, are most likely to increase off-farm employment 
 of plantable farm families in the Netherlands. However, in the presence of the (fear/stopping of behavior) to join off-farm 
 activities, the possible result of the CAP-reforms 
 cannot be fully (understood/made real/achieved). The results also suggest that 
 there is an different policy option for government 
 helping action if there is a need to make families 
 (branch out into different things) the ways in which they gain their job. 
 In the long run, the government can chase after policies such 
 as (helping increase/showing in a good way) education to enable farm families to 
 secure off-farm jobs more easily. In the short-run, 
 off-farm employment can be increased by reducing 
 fears, such as farm families' access to different 
 information sources, to join off-farm activities. 
 
